data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new `Span<T>` / `ReadOnlySpan<T>` conversions change overload resolution. Your `array.Contains(num)` now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)`** instead of `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees can't represent span-based calls, so it throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

This applies broadly â€” `Reverse()`, `Contains()`, and other LINQ methods on arrays can now resolve to span-based overloads. The same `.AsEnumerable()` or explicit `Enumerable.*` pattern fixes all of them.
